ut how collaborating with the Cylons, the original enemy of the 12 colonies, is a complete mistake, and he claims that [[Laura Roslin|President Roslin]] and [[William Adama|Admiral Adama]] are proposing this only to stay in power.  Following that, he makes a proposal that Cylons should only be allowed to board ships in the fleet with the crew's permission. The Quorum votes unanimously with the exception of [[Lee Adama]] for the proposal, thus accepting it.\n\nLaura Roslin refuses to stay in office as president throughout the entire episode. She throws away her cancer-fighting medication and starts jogging around the ship's corridors. There, she meets Admiral Adama, who tries to convince her that she is needed right now and must step back into office, to which she replies that she does not want to be used in any kind of plan anymore and does not want to play any role, and that she deserves to live, after all that has happened.  Adama grudgingly agrees, and Roslin tells him that he deserves to live a little as well. She kisses him and leaves.\n\nIn a lower deck, [[Gaius Baltar]] speaks before to a gathering.  He states that they should not have to excuse themselves before [[Cylon (reimagining)#Religion|God]], but that God should come down and beg for their forgiveness, since they have not sinned, but he led them to the desperate situation they are in now.\n\nGalen Tyrol is present during Baltar's speech, and he sees [[List of Battlestar Galactica characters#Hot Dog|Hot Dog]], a Viper pilot, there as well. The two exchange long, intense stares, and Galen realizes that Hot Dog is the father of Specialist [[Cally Henderson Tyrol]]'s child, a fact which Hot Dog admits when Tyrol approaches and confronts him. Tyrol punches him, and they engage in an intense fistfight in the middle of Baltar's speech. Tyrol later brings Hot Dog into sickbay, both of them sporting fresh bruises, telling him that it is now his turn to watch the child.\n\nThe fleet's [[tylium]] ship, the ''Hitei Kan'', defects, making an [[Faster-than-light|FTL]] jump to coordinates unknown to the rest of the fleet with the exception of [[Tom Zarek]], who instructed the tylium ship to do so. After the ship leaves, [[William Adama]] has [[Tom Zarek]] arrested and blackmails him into revealing the location of the ship by airing his 'dirty laundry' using alleged information of criminal acts of Zarek's during his time as politician. Zarek gives in and reveals the location of the ship to Adama. When Adama later hands the dossier to Tigh for him to give it to Mr. Hoshi, it becomes apparent that he was only bluffing, as the dossier was composed of laundry reports.\n\nIn the aftermath, [[Felix Gaeta]] meets with [[Tom Zarek]]. Tom Zarek promises that there will be consequences to what has happened, and Felix Gaeta agrees, stating that in his opinion everything is going wrong, and that there has to be someone to make it right again. He asks Zarek whether he is that man. Zarek replies that he is one of them, but that he needs a partner. Gaeta states that as of now, he has one, and shakes hands with Zarek.\n\n[[Sharon Agathon]] and other crew jump to the tylium ship's coordinates, and manage to bring it back. Admiral Adama receives notification of the tylium ship's return, accepting the call while in his quarters, in bed with [[Laura Roslin]]. She shows some interest in the news, and he asks her if she now cares. She responds in the negative, and hangs up the phone, and he laughs.\n\n==Production==\nThe episode was directed by [[Ronald D. Moore]], his directorial debut.<ref name=\"verheiden\">{{cite web|url=http://verheiden.blogspot.com/2008/03/battlestar-rolls-on-tuesday.html|title=Battlestar Rolls On Tuesday...|date=March 24, 2008|accessdate=2009-01-22|last=Verheiden|first=Mark| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090131210022/http://verheiden.blogspot.com/2008/03/battlestar-rolls-on-tuesday.html| archivedate= 31 January 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Ratings==\nTotal viewership for same-day viewing for \"A Disquiet Follows My Soul\" dropped nearly 20 percent from the previous week's episode, to just 1.7 million.<ref>[http://www.eonline.com/uberblog/b81029_fired_up_over_burn_notice_new_worry.html Ryan, Joal. \"Fired Up Over Burn Notice; New Worry for Jimmy Fallon?\" ''Entertainment Weekly.'' January 27, 2009.]</ref><ref>[http://tvbythenumbers.com/2009/01/27/obama-inauguration-wwe-raw-and-burn-notice-lead-weekly-cable-viewing/11610 Seidman, Robert. \"Updated: Obama Inauguration, WWE RAW and Burn Notice Lead Weekly Cable Viewing.\" TVBytheNumbers.com. January 27, 2009.]</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\nAlan Sepinwall of ''[[The Star-Ledger]]'' felt that the \"Gaeta and Zarek scenes through the episode crackled, especially Felix confronting Kara.\"<ref name=\"sepinwall\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nj.com/entertainment/index.ssf/2009/01/battlestar_galactica_a_disquie.html |title=Battlestar Galactica, \"A Disquiet Follows My Soul\": Okay, what's next? |accessdate=2009-03-10 |last=Sepinwall |first=Alan |coauthors= |date=2009-01-23 |work= |publisher=[[The Star-Ledger]]}}</ref> Maureen Ryan of the ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'' also enjoyed Starbuck's showdown with Gaeta, as well as the final scene of Roslin and Adama, and seeing a drunk, angry, and bitter Baltar.<ref name=\"maureenryan\">{{cite web|url=http://featuresblogs.chicagotribune.com/entertainment_tv/2009/01/battlestar-galactica-ron-moore-disquiet-follows-my-soul.html |title='Battlestar Galactica's' Ron Moore discusses 'A Disquiet Follows My Soul' |accessdate=2009-03-10 |last=Ryan |first=Maureen |coauthors= |date=2009-01-23 |work= |publisher=[[Chicago Tribune]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090301030135/http://featuresblogs.chicagotribune.com/entertainment_tv/2009/01/battlestar-galactica-ron-moore-disquiet-follows-my-soul.html |archivedate=1 March 2009 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [[BattlestarWiki:A Disquiet Follows My Soul|\"A Disquiet Follows My Soul\"]] at Battlestar Wiki\n* [http://www.syfy.com/battlestar/episodes/season/4/episode/414/a_disquiet_follows_my_soul \"A Disquiet Follows My Soul\"] at [[Syfy]]\n* {{tv.com episode|battlestar-galactica/a-disquiet-follows-my-soul-1242058}}\n* {{IMDb episode|0993913}}\n\n{{Battlestar Galactica (2004 TV series) episodes}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Disquiet Follows My Soul, A}}\n[[Category:2009 American television episodes]]\n[[Category:Battlestar Galactica (season 4) episodes]]\n", "name_user": "DonRobodroid", "label": "safe", "comment": "Changed episode number to 12, according to Wikipedia overview page and Blu-ray booklet.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/A_Disquiet_Follows_My_Soul"}
{"title_page": "Jonas Greene", "text_new": "'''Sir Jonas Greene''' (1767-1828) was an Irish [[barrister]] and magistrate who held the office of [[Recorder of Dublin]].\n\nHe was born in [[Dublin]], the eldest son of Richard Greene. He was [[called to the Bar]] and in 1822 he was made Recorder of Dublin and [[knighted]]. The Recorder was the chief magistrate for Dublin city, with the overall responsibility for keeping the peace. The office was an onerous one. Greene from the available evidence seems to have been diligent and hard-working. A debate on the duties of the Recorder in the [[English House of Commons]] three years after his death revealed that he held two sessions of his court every week, with extra sessions as the workload required.\n\nHe married in 1790 the popular Dublin [[actress]]  Marianne Hitchcock. She was the daughter of Robert Hitchcock, the author and playwright, and his wife Sarah, who like her daughter was a popular actress. They had at least two sons of whom the eldest, [[Richard Wilson Greene]], followed his father to the Bar and became a senior [[judge]].\n\nJonas died at [[Bath, Somerset|Bath]] in March 1828. Marianne died in 1854.\n\n[[File:Richard Wilson Greene.jpg|thumb|Photo of Richard Wilson Greene, Irish judge, eldest son of Sir Jonas Greene]]\n\n==Sources==\n* ''Annual Register for the Year 1828''\n* Ball, F. Elrington  ''The Judges in Ireland 1221-1921'' John Murray London 1926\n* ''Hansard's Parliamentary Debates 1831''\n*  Montgomery-Massingberd, Hugh   ''Burke's Irish Family Records'' London 1976\n\n[[Category:Recorders of Dublin]]\n[[Category:Irish barristers]]\n[[Category:People from Dublin (city)]]\n[[Category:1767 births]]\n[[Category:1828 deaths]]\n", "text_old": "'''Sir Jonas Greene''' (1767-1828) was an Irish [[barrister ]] and magistrate who held the office of [[Recorder of Dublin]].\n\nHe was born in [[Dublin]], the eldest son of Richard Greene. He was [[called to the Bar]] and in 1822 he was made Recorder of Dublin and [[knighted]]. The Recorder was the chief magistrate for Dublin city, with the overall responsibility for keeping the peace. THe office was an onerous one. Greene from the available evidence seems to have been diligent and hard-working. A debate on the duties of the Recorder in the [[English House of Commons]] three years after his death revealed that he held two sessions of his court every week, with extra sessions as the workload required.\n\nHe married in 1790 the popular Dublin [[actress]]  Marianne Hitchcock. She was the daughter of Robert Hitchcock, the author and playwright, and his wife Sarah, who like her daughter was was a popular actress. They had at least two sons of whom the eldest, [[Richard Wilson Greene]], followed his father to the Bar and became a senior [[judge]].\n\nJonas died at [[Bath, Somerset|Bath]] in March 1828. Marianne died in 1854.\n\n[[File:Richard Wilson Greene.jpg|thumb|Photo of Richard Wilson Greene, Irish judge, eldest son of Sir Jonas Greene]]\n\n==Sources==\n* ''Annual Register for the Year 1828''\n* Ball, F. Elrington  ''The Judges in Ireland 1221-1921'' John Murray London 1926\n* ''Hansard's Parliamentary Debates 1831''\n*  Montgomery-Massingberd, Hugh   ''Burke's Irish Family Records'' London 1976\n\n[[Category:Recorders of Dublin]]\n[[Category:Irish barristers]]\n[[Category:People from Dublin (city)]]\n", "name_user": "CAPTAIN RAJU", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up,typo(s) fixed: THe \u2192 The, was was \u2192 was", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jonas_Greene"}
